{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox person | name = Francis Arthur Powell Aveling | image = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1875|12|25}}<ref name=amjopsy>{{cite journal| journal = American Journal of Psychology | title = Francis Aveling: 1875-1941| author = Raymond B. Cattell | volume = 54 | issue = 4 | date = October 1941 | pages = 608–610| jstor=1417217}} </ref> | birth_place = [[St. Catharines]], [[Ontario]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1941|03|06|1875|12|25}} | death_place = | death_cause = | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = psychologist | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | height = <!-- {{height|m=}} --> | weight = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} --> | title = | predecessor = | successor = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = Ethel Dancy<ref name="amjopsy"/> | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | module = | module2 = | module3 = | module4 = | module5 = | module6 = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | box_width = }} '''Francis Arthur Powell Aveling''' [[Doctor of Divinity|DD]] [[Doctor of Science|D.Sc]] [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] [[Doctor of Letters|DLit]] [[Military Cross|MC]]<ref name=amjopsy/><ref name=longaz6462>{{cite news | title = London Gazette | date=3 June 1918 |pages=6462–6463| url = http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/30716/supplements/6462}}</ref> [[Order of Christ (Portugal)|ComC]]<ref name=longaz12415>{{cite news | title = London Gazette | date=7 October 1919 |pages=12414–12415 | url = http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/31586/supplements/12415}}</ref><ref name=brjopsy/> (25 December 1875&nbsp;–&nbsp;6 March 1941) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[psychology|psychologist]] and [[Roman Catholic]] priest.<ref name=amjopsy/> He married Ethel Dancy of Steyning, Sussex in 1925.<ref name=amjopsy/><ref name=brjopsy/>
==Education== Aveling went to [[Ridley College|Bishop Ridley College]] in [[Ontario]], before studying at [[McGill University]] in Quebec, [[Keble College]] at [[Oxford University]], England, and the [[Canadian College]] Rome (Pontificio [[Collegio Canadese]]).<ref>Roman Colleges. (1913). ''Catholic Encyclopedia''. New York: Robert Appleton Company.</ref> There he earned his [[doctor of divinity]] degree.<ref name=amjopsy/><ref name=brjopsy>{{cite journal | journal = British Journal of Psychology | title = Obituary Notice Francis Aveling 1875-1941 | volume = 32 | issue = 1 | pages= 1–4 | date = July 1941 | url= http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.2044-8295.1941.tb01005.x/abstract | doi=10.1111/j.2044-8295.1941.tb01005.x}}</ref> In 1910, Aveling obtained a [[doctor of philosophy]] degree at the age of 35 years from the [[Catholic University of Leuven (1834–1968)|University of Louvain]] (his advisor was Michotte), and in 1912 he was recipient of a [[doctor of science]] degree from the [[University of London]], and received the [[Carpenter Medal]] following his work ''On the Consciousness of the Universal and the Individual: A Contribution to the Phenomenology of the Thought Process''.<ref name=amjopsy/><ref name=brjopsy/> Subsequently, Aveling received his [[doctor of letters]] degree from the [[University of London]].<ref name=amjopsy/>
==Career==
Aveling taught at [[University College, London]] from 1912 as a Lecturer (Assistant Professor), under the leadership of [[Charles Spearman]], until the [[First World War]].<ref name=brjopsy/> During that war he served in France as a [[Military Chaplain|chaplain]] in the [[British Army]], after which he returned to the [[University of London]].<ref name=amjopsy/> In 1922, he transferred to [[King's College, London]] where he was promoted to [[reader (academic rank)|reader]] (associate professor), and later to professor of psychology.<ref name=brjopsy/> Aveling authored several books.<ref>Bredin. H. (2005) Aveling, Francis Arthur Powell (1875-1941). In S. Brown (Ed.), ''Dictionary of Twentieth Century British Philosophers'' (pp. 40-41). Bristol, UK: Thoemmes Continuum. {{ISBN|1 84371 096X}}</ref> He was the doctoral advisor of [[Raymond Cattell]]<ref>Sheehy, N. (2004). ''Fifty Key Thinkers in Psychology'' (p.61). London: Routledge. {{ISBN|0-203-44765-4}}; {{ISBN|0-203-75589-8}}; {{ISBN|0-415-16774-4}}; {{ISBN|0-415-16775-2}}.</ref> From 1926 until 1929, Aveling was also a president of the [[British Psychological Society]].<ref name=amjopsy/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://hopc.bps.org.uk/histres/bpshistory/presidents$.cfm | title=Presidents of the British Psychological Society | work=History of Psychology Centre|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> Aveling was a member of the [[Council of the International Congresses]], of the [[Aristotelian Society]], of the council and advisory board of the [[National Institute of Industrial Psychology]], of the council of the [[British Institute of Philosophical Studies]] and of the [[Child Guidance Council]].{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
